ce:section.ce:para:
The synthesis of NCDs from sugarcane bagasse agricultural waste was carried out by hydrothermal treatment of cellulose diacetate at 240 °C for 14 h as shown in Scheme 1
                        . Sugarcane bagasse was firstly used to isolate fibrous cellulose as a white powder [33]. To produce cellulose diacetate, a solution of DMSO and TBAA was used to treat the produced cellulose fibers, and then the solution was neutralized with acetic anhydride [34]. Diluted solution of NH4OH(aq) was used as a passivation agent and reaction medium instead of using the expensive and dangerous organic passivation substances, which commonly introduce many terminal amines [35]. As appeared in Fig. 1
                        , the ideal QY of NCDs was determined by examining the mass ratio of NH4OH to cellulose diacetate. The QY was increased from 11.07 to 24.81% by changing the ammonium hydroxide mass ratio from 1:0 to 1:12, respectively. The QY would decrease to 23.56% when the mass ratio was raised to 1:20. NCDs with QY as high as 24.81% was introduced using different mass ratios of ammonium hydroxide and cellulose diacetate. Previous reports on degradation and carbonization of cellulosic materials have shown that NCDs can be produced by a hydrolytic process of cellulose diacetate and subsequent condensation of small fragments to produce NCDs. In a cellulose dicetate derivative, glycoside linkages bind glucose-like units together [37]. In NH4OH(aq), glycoside bond breaking and deacetylation of cellulose diacetate could yield ethanoic acid, fructose, and additional cellulose diacetate intermediates [38]. The carbon structure of NCDs was produced by further condensation and carbonization of the previously identified cellulose diacetate fragments during the subsequent hydrothermal treatment. For successful passivation of paper surface with nitrogen, nucleophilic substitution of ammonia to the cellulose carbon's hydroxyls is the key [39]. The TEM images of NCDs were studied before and after exposure to tetracycline to reveal almost similar diameters of 5–8 nm (Fig. 2
                        ). NCDs do not have a lattice structure, according to prior studies [40]. Two strong XRD bands of cellulose diacetate were detected at 7.4° and 20.1° due to the crystallization phase of cellulose diacetate. NCDs showed two wide signals at 15.2 and 23.0° due to the carbon's amorphous phase (Fig. 3
                        ). FTIR spectra were also used to identify NCDs surface functional substituents (Fig. 4
                        ). In addition to the stretch vibration at 3454 cm−1, bending vibrations at 1238 cm−1 and 719 cm−1 were detected to be related to both NH and OH groups, respectively, which proves that cellulose diacetate has been successfully doped with nitrogen. The presence of sulfur in NCDs was represented by SO3 and C–O stretch vibrations at 1009 cm−1 [34,41].

Sugarcane bagasse is an agricultural waste found in abundance and at low-costs. It is a byproduct of the sugarcane industry where 650, 350 to 27.6 million tons are made annually in the three largest producers, Brazil, India, and the USA [43]. Sugarcane biomass mainly contains cellulose (44–59%), serving as the main carbon source, lignin (28–29%), and hemicellulose (8–27%). Chung et al. used sugarcane bagasse agricultural waste to develop biocompatible CDs by a hydrothermal method and blending hydroxyapatite nanoparticles by a sol-gel method at 190 °C [44]. The nanocomposite was tested for acetaminophen loading and release kinetics for drug delivery and tracing applications. Eslami et al. produced green CD-based nonabsorbent materials for adsorption and removal of naphthalene contaminates in water bodies [45]. Activated CDs were extracted from sugarcane bagasse by a hydrothermal carbonization method in the presence of a KOH activator. Thambiraj et al. used a top-down technique of chemical oxidation and exfoliation of sugarcane carbon by combustion at 60 °C, then CDs were extracted by a toluene solvent giving a quantum yield of 18.7% [46]. This preparation improved the fluorescence yield for three different bandwidths ranging between 283 and 380. It has been feasible for smart products to respond to external stimuli to result in unique variables such as colorimetric and fluorescence changes [47]. Fluorescent sensors are one kind of smart material that changes color upon exposure to light stimulus. The significance of sensor strips has been increasing lately due to their straightforward preparation and usage, suitable composition, and possible applications in a wide range of disciplines, including environmental and medical sensing tools, and security alarms. Fig. 6
                         shows SEM images of the fluorescent NCDs film deposited onto a paper strip, confirming that a thin film of NCDs was successfully deposited onto the paper surface. NCDs were equally distributed throughout the cellulose paper surface due to their nanoscale character. SEM micrographs of coated strips revealed no physical alterations in the structure of strip cellulose fibers as compared to blank strip [42]. The chemical composition of NDCs6 at three points was examined using EDX (Table 1
                        ). Nearly identical elemental ratios were identified at the three different sites of NDCs6. The nitrogen and sulfur levels were reported at 13.96% and 1.29%, respectively. Those values were higher than in cellulose diacetate, proving a successful doping. Only ammonium hydroxide and cellulose diacetate were utilized in the preparation of NCDs, in which nitrogen was derived from the passivation agent (ammonium hydroxide) and carbon was derived from cellulose diacetate.
